				<outline text="&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.niallkennedy.com/blog/archives/2006/08/leaving-microsoft.html&quot;&gt;Niall Kennedy&lt;/a&gt;: &quot;I am leaving Microsoft to start my own company.&quot;" created="Tue, 08 Aug 2006 20:40:06 GMT"/>
				<outline text="&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.macintouch.com/specialreports/wwdc2006/index.html&quot;&gt;Macintouch reports&lt;/a&gt; on yesterday's Apple announcements. " created="Tue, 08 Aug 2006 16:06:21 GMT"/>
				<outline text="&lt;a href=&quot;http://wired.com/news/columns/cultofmac/0,71557-0.html?tw=wn_index_6&quot;&gt;Wired&lt;/a&gt;: &quot;He effortlessly sucks the audience into his famous 'reality distortion field,' a state of suspended disbelief that makes even mundane products seem like miracles of technology.&quot;" created="Tue, 08 Aug 2006 16:08:10 GMT"/>
				</outline>
			<outline text="August 7" created="Mon, 07 Aug 2006 05:00:01 GMT">
				<outline text="&lt;img src=&quot;http://images.scripting.com/archiveScriptingCom/2006/08/07/dp.gif&quot; width=&quot;61&quot; height=&quot;86&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; align=&quot;right&quot; hspace=&quot;15&quot; vspace=&quot;5&quot; alt=&quot;A picture named dp.gif&quot;&gt;Trying to find a  good summary of Apple's announcements. Here's what I've discerned: 1. A new Mac desktop with Intel processors. 2. A new version of the operating system. For me it's the first new version of the OS since I became a Mac user again in Sept of last year. The features I've seen so far don't excite me. But then when has an operating system ever had anything in it to get excited about? " created="Mon, 07 Aug 2006 21:07:57 GMT"/>
				<outline text="&lt;a href=&quot;http://blog.eweek.com/blogs/knowitall/archive/2006/08/07/12254.aspx&quot;&gt;Ed Cone&lt;/a&gt;: &quot;BusinessWeek's best bet is to say, 'We goofed. We wrote an interesting article about an interesting subject, but we made a pretty bad mistake in the way we headlined the story.'&quot;" created="Mon, 07 Aug 2006 20:46:51 GMT"/>
				<outline text="&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.wordyard.com/2006/08/07/business-week-followup/&quot;&gt;Scott Rosenberg&lt;/a&gt;: &quot;The magazine can either publish a correction, which I doubt it will ever do, or live with the diminished credibility it deserves.&quot;" created="Tue, 08 Aug 2006 00:22:10 GMT"/>
